\title{Sparse 3\textdegree{} Node Enrichment in Eurasian Monument Corpora}

\author{Seth Tenenbaum\thanks{ORCID: \href{https://orcid.org/0009-0008-5797-2498}{0009-0008-5797-2498}.
Correspondence: seth@fourthtemple.com}\\
Independent Scholar, USA}

\maketitle

\abstract{
We report a two-stage observational study of Eurasian monument
geography. In the exploratory stage, domed and stupa-related sites
within the UNESCO Cultural and Mixed World Heritage corpus
($N=\NclusterTotal$) showed elevated node-neighborhood clustering
conditional on a specified 3\textdegree{} / $\sim$35\textdegree{}E
longitude frame: modest full-corpus Tier-A+ enrichment with stronger
dome/stupa behavior, and the dome/stupa signal locates in the subset's
own longitude distribution (Null~A, $p=\geoNullDomeBootP$). In the
validation stage, the same frame was applied without modification to
the externally curated Wikidata Q180987 stupa corpus ($N=\npcNStupa{}$),
assembled independently of this analysis. The primary finding is
monument-type-specific phase concentration: the Wikidata stupa corpus
shows independently significant Rayleigh phase concentration at
$T=3^\circ$ ($R=\circConcStupaR{}$, perm-$p=\circConcStupaP{}$).
The full UNESCO corpus shows no global periodicity at this period
($R=\circConcUnescoR{}$, perm-$p=\circConcUnescoP{}$, ns), and
Watson's $U^2$/Kuiper tests confirm the two corpora have detectably
different phase distributions ($p=\circWatsonPUnescoStupa{}$,
$p=\circKuiperPUnescoStupa{}$). A Normalized Phasor Consensus
(NPC) test provides supplementary anchor-concordance evidence
($K \geq \npcDomeStupaK{}$ in all monument pairs, consensus grid
lines within \npcTwoGridDeltaE\textdegree{}--\npcDomeStupaGridDeltaE\textdegree{}
of 35\textdegree{}E); non-nested two-corpus tests do not reach $p<0.05$
individually. Substituting the Americas sub-corpus collapses
concordance ($K=\npcNegThreeK{}$, ns), as does including OWTRAD
trade-route nodes ($K=\npcAllK{}$, ns). The finding is
monument-type specific, not corpus-level: the 3\textdegree{} phase
concentration belongs to hemispherical monument architecture, not to
the UNESCO heritage list as a whole. The result is bounded by the
null global periodogram, marginal anchor-discovery correction,
geographic dependence, and the absence of evidence for universal
periodicity, historical intentionality, metrology, or a unique Gerizim
origin.
}

\bigskip

\noindent\textbf{Keywords:}
template alignment, spatial statistics, Levant, UNESCO World Heritage,
3-degree harmonics, selected-frame analysis, circular statistics,
monument distribution, anchor consensus

